The Mighty Meeple is far and away the best game store in the Charlotte Metro area, if not the entire state of North Carolina. It is my immediate recommendation to anyone looking for a space to engage with board games, trading card games, miniatures games, TTRPGs, and more.

The store has an excellent selection of product at fair prices, including a generous rewards points system. The staff is friendly and knowledgeable of the products, and most employees are passionate enough about the products that they’ll be the same people you see playing in the store. Dave, one of the owners, is extraordinarily friendly and present in the store, and goes above and beyond to accommodate different groups and individuals to ensure they have a welcoming, safe, and most of all fun experience.

The Mighty Meeple offers a community play space with a wide selection of games to demo at no cost. The play area is large compared to other stores, and it is always tidy and clean. They have sections dedicated to miniatures games as well so that there is no competing for play space. Their concession area is well-stocked with various snacks, baked goods, and beverages. If you drink, they also have a nice selection of beer and ciders on draught, as well as a selection of wine.

The store actively supports and fosters communities. They have been immensely supportive of our efforts to kickstart a Pauper Magic: the Gathering night, providing free prize support and sectioning off an area of the play space to reserve for our use. This is the case for many different games, not just Magic. Mighty Meeple has an event of some kind going on almost every day, so that those interested in meeting up with like-minded individuals have a space to do so. They put in the effort to maintain an impressive scheduling board in their play space so that you can be comfortable in knowing when different events of interest are happening. The Mighty Meeple is an important “third place” for many of its patrons and does a great job maintaining that role. I have met many of my close friends through events that Meeple has offered.

The Mighty Meeple is the gold standard for game stores, and I encourage you to check it out.

The Meeple is an exceptional LGS in every regard. They have definitely earned the “featured LGS” designation on the WoTC website. As someone newer to MTG it has been really hard to find a welcoming and accessible shop to play at and meet new players. The Meeple team works hard to make people comfortable, help them improve their game, and help them meet new players. The staff pitch play nights and get excited when you show up- they even walked me around and introduced me to some regular players my first game night to help me find a pod and get started. They also have a LOT of inventory. Whatever I need is typically in stock. Are the singles/prices higher than online? Yes. But I happily pay a bit more (typically ~10% more than the lowest TCG Player price) in exchange for all of the additional value we get from the shop. Some reviews about the shop being discriminatory or exclusive surprised me - as a regular shopper and new weekly Commander player, I always see a very diverse player population and the staff are very welcoming. Don’t give up on the local play groups! Try the Meeple!

The Mighty Meeple is far and away the best game store in the Charlotte Metro area, if not the entire state of North Carolina. It is my immediate recommendation to anyone looking for a space to engage with board games, trading card games, miniatures games, TTRPGs, and more.

The store has an excellent selection of product at fair prices, including a generous rewards points system. The staff is friendly and knowledgeable of the products, and most employees are passionate enough about the products that they’ll be the same people you see playing in the store. They have sections dedicated to miniatures games as well so that there is no competing for play space. Their concession area is well-stocked with various snacks, baked goods, and beverages. If you drink, they also have a nice selection of beer and ciders on draught, as well as a selection of wine.

The store actively supports and fosters communities. They have been immensely supportive of our efforts to kickstart a Pauper Magic: the Gathering night, providing free prize support and sectioning off an area of the play space to reserve for our use. This is the case for many different games, not just Magic. Mighty Meeple has an event of some kind going on almost every day, so that those interested in meeting up with like-minded individuals have a space to do so. They put in the effort to maintain an impressive scheduling board in their play space so that you can be comfortable in knowing when different events of interest are happening. The Mighty Meeple is an important “third place” for many of its patrons and does a great job maintaining that role. I have met many of my close friends through events that Meeple has offered.

The Mighty Meeple is the gold standard for game stores, and I encourage you to check it out.

The Mighty Meeple has a lot going for it: huge selection, knowledgeable and (usually) helpful staff, and a massive play area. I also appreciate how strict and consistent they are about their mask policy. But there's one glaring issue that keeps me from spending another penny: the owner is abusive towards his employees, sometimes even in front of customers. I've known various previous employees, I've seen it firsthand, and I was even a victim myself during my (luckily) brief employment there.

I'm a big fan of supporting local businesses, so allow me to suggest a few nearby competitors like Buzz City or Scott's Collectibles. You can shop there and know that your money won't end in the pocket of a cruel and abusive employer.

The store itself is nice, but totally lost my business since it turns out they're scalpers. They are charging almost 2x retail for something that is still in print and trying to pass it off as "market price." These guys are retailers. They should be charging retail (or maybe SLIGHT above retail). Can you imagine if Target started charging hundreds of extra dollars for PS5s because of "market price?" If this was a single rare card or out-of-print product, sure, charging extra makes sense. But I know other FLGSs that charge retail for the same product, so these guys are just being opportunistic scalpers.
